value.value: Chronic inflammatory condition characterised by infiltration of primarily lymphocytes.
Nodular inflammatory reaction, containing compactly grouped epithelioid cells, giant cells, and other macrophages. The basic inflammatory unit is termed a granuloma.
Acute inflammatory reaction in which the predominant histological change is rapid diffuse necrosis throughout the affected tissue.
A tumor resulting from abnormal and uncontrolled autonomous new cell growth (proliferation)that may be benign or malignant.
Tumors of the skin, its constituent structures and glands including the mammary gland, apocrine and eccrine glands, hair follicles and associated structures.
Defect in the structure or function of the mitochondria.
Carcinoma of the glandular epithelium of apocrine glands (M-8401/3).
Benign neoplasm of the epithelium of apocrine glands (M-8401/0).
Malignant carcinoma of the ceruminous gland (M-8420/3).
Benign adenomatous neoplasia of the ceruminous glands of the external auditory meatus (M-8420/0).
Tumor derived from eccrine sweat glands composed of clear glycogen rich cells. ( M-84020 ).
Malignant neoplasm of the eccrine gland (M-8413/3).
Benign neoplasm of the eccrine gland (M-8408/0).
Papillary form of eccrine sweat gland adenoma. (M -8408/0).
Benign apocrine sweat gland tumor (8405/0).
Malignant neoplasm of the sebaceous cells - rare areas of differentiation, severe nuclear atypia (M-8410/3).
Defect in the structure or function of the peroxysomes.
Adenoma of sebaceous cells; regular architecture of gland not mantained. Large numbers of immature germinative cells present. Mitoses. (M-8410/0).
A benign, often multiple, sometimes eruptive neoplasm of the sweat gland ducts composed of very small round cysts. (M-8407/0).
Multiple small benign nodules derived from basal cells of hair follicles enclosing small cornified cell containing cysts. (M-8100/0).
Well circumscribed tumor of the basal cells of the epidermis. Rare mitotic figures, benign. (M8147/0).
Malignant neoplasm of the basal cells of the epidermis with local invasion. (M-8090/3).
Tumor of venous or arterial vessels or capillaries.
.A benign neoplasm of fibrous tissue in which there are multiple large and small dilated vascular channels ( M9160/0).
An intradermal capillary telangiectasis with hyperkeratosis and acanthosis (M-9141/0).
A benign neoplasm frequently arising in the cerebellum composed of capillary vessel forming endothelial cells and stromal cells. (M-9161/1).
Defect in the structure or function of the plasma membrane.
Neoplasm derived from endothelial cells. May be of capillary or cavernous type with large vascular channels. (M-9130/0 + M-9120/0 respectively).
A vascular, usually benign, neoplasm composed of round and spindle cells derived from the pericytes and surround endothelium-lined vessels. (M-9150/0/1/3).
Malignant neoplasm derived from pluripotential mesenchymal stem cells or endothelial cells of blood vessels. (M-9120/3).
Neoplasm of the neurones, glia or meninges of the CNS.
Glioma derived from astrocytes, both benign and malignant forms (M-9400/3).

value.value: Malignant neoplasm derived from the epithelial cells of the choroid plexus. (M-9390/3).
Benign neoplasm derived from the epithelial cells of the choroid plexus. (M-9390/0).
Neoplasm derived from the ependymal cells lining the ventricles and aqueduct of the brain and the central canal of the spinal cord. Malignant or benign. (M-9391/3).

definition.value: Also see general scheme in Weiss, W.W, Israel, M. Cobbs, C., et al. (2002) Oncogene 21, 7453-7463.

value.value: Neoplasm derived from astrocytes and oligodendrocytes. (M-9380/3, M-9440/3).

definition.value: Also see comments in: Weiss, W.W, Israel, M. Cobbs, C., et al. (2002) Oncogene 21, 7453-7463.

value.value: Degenerative process characteristic of a particular tissue.
Neoplasm derived from the primitive neurectodermal cells of the cerebellum. (M-9470/3). May be considered by some authorities a synonym of PNET in the CNS.

definition.value: Also see Weiss, W.W, Israel, M. Cobbs, C., et al. (2002) Oncogene 21, 7453-7463.

definition.value: Benign or malignant neoplasm derived from the meninges. (M-9530/0).

value.value: Benign or malignant neoplasm derived form oligodendrocytes (M-9450/3).

definition.value: Also see Weiss, W.W, Israel, M. Cobbs, C., et al. (2002) Oncogene 21, 7453-7463.

value.value: Tumors showing multiple histological componants/differentiation.
Mixed tumor of glandular epithelia with squamous and glandular diffferentiation. (M-8570/3).
Possible origin from smooth muscle cells or pluripotential embryonic mesenchymal cells. May show up to three cellular componants including carcinoma and sarcoma type appearances. (M-8980/3).
A benign or malignant neoplasm, which may be cystic, developing from the epithelium of Rathke`s pouch and occuring with or close to the pituitary gland. (M-9350/1).
Neoplasm showing multiple phases, derived from mesoderm (M-8951/3).
Most commonly a salivary gland carcinoma of low grade malignancy composed of mucous, epidermoid, and intermediate cells. (M-8430/3).
Absence of hair or loss of hair.
Neoplasm usually of the uterus or adnexae containing carcinomatous and sarcomatous elements, sometimes with third or fourth components. (M-8950/3).
Embryonal tumor thought to be derived from metanephric blastema. Mono, bi or triphasic, sometimes with heterotypic differentiation. (M-8960/3).
